full_content.content: Common reasons your Whirlpool range is not working
The most common reasons your Whirlpool range is not working are an inoperative electronic control board, faulty igniter or a bad switch.
We can help! Our service technicians have repaired over
Whirlpool ranges. We can fix yours no matter where you bought it.
Most common repairs needed to fix a Whirlpool range

An inoperative electronic control board can lead to various failures in a range, including a lack of power or heating in the oven or surface element, or prevent the oven from turning off. This is because the board serves as the brain of the range, controlling crucial operations such as regulating oven temperatures, running cooling fans, and controlling cooking time. If the electronic control board malfunctions, it can disrupt communication between many different components. A failing board may cause a chattering or clicking noise from the range and may emit a burning odor. Due to the potential impact on multiple components, it is advisable to have a Sears Home Services professional conduct diagnostic tests on the board to confirm if replacement is necessary.
How to replace a range oven control board

A faulty range igniter can prevent a burner from igniting, resulting in no heat from the bake or broil burner in the oven, or from a surface burner. A failed igniter could also cause difficulty in lighting the burner, requiring multiple attempts to achieve ignition. The igniter may emit a clicking sound without successfully lighting the gas, indicating a malfunction. In some cases, the igniter may not produce any visible spark at all. An igniter failure can lead to delayed ignition, causing a noticeable delay between turning the knob and the burner lighting.

A bad surface element switch may make turning the surface element on or off difficult, or a damaged switch shaft may feel loose or wobbly. The malfunctioning switch could cause uneven heating or prevent the element from reaching the desired temperature. In some cases, the surface element may not turn on at all, or it may continue to heat even after the control is turned off, posing a safety risk. If you suspect the switch on your range is bad, have a Sears Home Services professional inspect the switch for you.
Radiant surface element on a range not working video
What to expect when you experience a Whirlpool range not working issue
How is the not working problem fixed?

Correcting most not working problems usually involves replacing the electronic control board, igniter or surface element switch. However, there are many potential causes, so a thorough diagnosis is key to fixing the problem. An accurate diagnosis is essential to understanding how much the repair will be.
Sears Home Services recommendations for a range that is not working

When the range is not working it can be for many reasons. To avoid replacing unneeded parts we recommend having a Sears Home Services professional perform diagnostic tests to identify the root cause of the problem. Our technicians are experienced at diagnosing all types of range failures; if you're in need of
, they can quickly determine the issue and make the necessary repairs.
What to look out for with a range not working diagnosis

Diagnosing modern appliances without proper knowledge and training can be difficult. Without using proper diagnostic techniques, fixing your range problem will only be achieved through changing parts on a hunch. Appliances, especially in the last 10 years, have become extremely advanced, and many models have electronic parts that are difficult to test. DIY repairs on the latest appliance models are becoming increasingly difficult.

If your Whirlpool stove is not heating up, there are several potential causes to consider. These issues can range from minor malfunctions to significant component failures. The most common reason is a faulty igniter, which is responsible for lighting the gas in your stove. If it’s not working, the stove won’t heat up. Signs of a faulty igniter include a clicking sound without ignition or no spark at all. Another potential cause is electronic control board failure, which manages all the functions of the stove. If it’s faulty, it can prevent the stove from heating. Look out for signs like the stove not turning on, random beeping, or an unresponsive keypad. For electric stoves, a damaged heating element can cause heating issues. Visible signs of damage or an element that doesn’t glow red when turned on are indicators of a problem.

When the oven in your Whirlpool stove stops working, it can be due to several reasons. One common cause is a burned-out bake element, which is crucial for oven heating. If it’s burned out, the oven won’t heat properly, and you might notice uneven cooking or no heat at all. Another issue could be the thermostat, which regulates the oven temperature. If it’s malfunctioning, the oven might not reach the desired temperature or could overheat. Additionally, door seal problems can lead to heat escaping, causing the oven to work inefficiently or not heat up to the correct temperature.

Inspect and replace faulty components by visually inspecting the igniter, control board, and heating elements. Replacing these parts can often resolve the issue. For complex issues, especially with electronic control boards, it’s best to seek professional help. Technicians can perform precise diagnostics and repairs. Regular cleaning and maintenance can prevent many of these problems. Ensure the igniter is clean and free from debris, and inspect elements for wear and tear periodically.
Whirlpool Stove Oven Not Working: Troubleshooting and Solutions
If you’re experiencing issues with your Whirlpool stove oven not working, understanding the potential causes and solutions can help you address these issues more effectively.
Common Causes of a Whirlpool Stove Oven Not Working

A faulty igniter is one of the most common reasons for a Whirlpool stove oven not working. The igniter is responsible for lighting the gas in the oven. When it fails, the oven will not heat up. Signs of a faulty igniter include a clicking sound without ignition, no visible spark, or delayed ignition. To address this issue, inspect the igniter for any visible damage or debris. Cleaning the igniter carefully might help, but if it still doesn’t work, it may need to be replaced. This task can be done by a DIY enthusiast with the proper tools and precautions, but professional help is highly recommended for accurate diagnosis and replacement.

Another frequent cause is a burned-out bake element in electric ovens, which can prevent the oven from heating properly. Symptoms of a burned-out bake element include the oven not heating up and visible damage to the element. To fix this, visually inspect the bake element for any signs of burning or damage. If the element appears damaged, it should be replaced.

A malfunctioning thermostat, which regulates the temperature within the oven, can also be a culprit. If the thermostat malfunctions, the oven might not reach the desired temperature or could overheat. Indications of a failed thermostat include the oven not reaching the set temperature, overheating, and inconsistent temperature during cooking. Testing the thermostat using an oven thermometer can reveal if it’s accurately reading temperatures. If not, the thermostat may need to be recalibrated or replaced.

Issues with the electronic control board can cause a range of problems, including the oven not working at all. The electronic control board acts as the brain of your oven, controlling all its functions. Symptoms of electronic control board issues include the oven not turning on, random beeping, and an unresponsive keypad. Diagnosing and replacing an electronic control board can be complex, so it’s best to have a professional technician handle this repair to ensure proper testing and replacement.

Regular maintenance can prevent many issues with your Whirlpool stove oven not working. Keeping the igniter and bake element clean and free from debris is essential. Periodically inspect the oven’s components, such as the bake element and thermostat, for signs of wear and tear. Scheduling regular maintenance with a professional ensures that all components are functioning correctly.

By understanding these common causes and solutions, you can troubleshoot and address issues with your Whirlpool stove oven not working more effectively. Regular maintenance and timely repairs can help keep your oven in optimal working condition, ensuring it serves you well for years to come.

full_content.content: Why isn’t my Whirlpool range working?
A blown fuse, tripped circuit breaker, or malfunctioning control board could prevent the range from working. Inspect these components for faults or damage.
Could a blown fuse stop my Whirlpool range from working?
Yes, if the fuse is blown, the range will not receive power. Replacing the fuse should restore functionality.
How can I fix my Whirlpool range if it’s not working?
Check the fuse, circuit breaker, and control board for issues. Replacing any damaged parts should restore the range’s functionality.
What should I do if my Whirlpool range still isn’t working after replacing the fuse?
If the range continues not to work, the control board or wiring may need professional inspection and repair.

What is a Dual Fuel Range?
A dual fuel range combines the precision of an electric oven with the responsiveness of a gas cooktop, offering the best of both worlds for cooking enthusiasts.
